Scotland's independent schools hold a good reputation for academic excellence, and this has continued in 2018 with another set of exceptional results in the exams, which are only complemented by individual and joint success in sports, art, music and other community endeavours.
With more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Independent Schools Council (SCIS), seek to provide the best level of service to their pupils and parents.
Independent schools are trying to prepare their pupils for further education and higher education, for the careers they choose and for their place as global citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a leading school curriculum, we see modern languages still being popular topics that are chosen in schools.
Nelson Mandela said: "If you talk to someone in a language they understand, it will remain in their memory.
If you talk to someone in their own language, that will stay in the heart."
This is a powerful message to remind us that we can't rely on English only when trying to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
Looking at the results of this year's exams, we can see that languages are at the top of the charts and include the highest passing rates in independent schools.
A total of 68 per cent of pupils who studied foreign languages have obtained a high A degree.
The data, collected from the 74 schools that are a member of SCIS, show that 72% of pupils have received a grade of A High in Mandarin, and that 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who got a grade of A high in Mandarin.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will definitely need in the future.
Now languages, such as subjects, are treated in the same way as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curriculum of independent schools and in other places.
A survey by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that a lack of language skills was responsible for 17 per cent of the reasons employers were unable to fill vacancies.
Therefore, there is a growing demand for languages in order to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more proposed job opportunities requiring languages, these skills are essential in a global environment. -
No matter what career one chooses, if that person has learned a second language, he will have a real advantage in the future of having such a long-term skill.
The ability to communicate directly with people in other countries will mean that a bilingual person will immediately step forward.
According to a poll by YouGov which included more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 73 per cent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation. In addition, French was the only language that was spoken by a percentage of double figures, which is 15 per cent.
This is the reason why investing in language teaching is important for children today.
Being able to speak a number of languages, especially those of developing economies, will give children a better chance of finding meaningful work.
In Scotland, all schools will be different in terms of the languages they will teach.
A number of schools will focus on classic modern languages, but other schools will teach languages that are considered the most important to the UK when looking around 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be a number of languages they can choose from in independent schools, and the schools will include teaching staff who specialize in this field.
Scotland's independent schools are committed to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever may be ahead of them.
At the moment, in a global business environment, it cannot be denied that languages are still vital to the country's future, so that must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered as "international communication skills."
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, variety and excellence for Scotland's young people.
It has to be done.
