Syria says it is ready to accept asylum seekers back voluntarily and is appealing for help to rebuild the country that has been devastated by seven years of war.
Speaking at the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said conditions were improving in the country.
"The situation on the ground is now more stable and safe, thanks to the fight against terrorism," he said.
The government is working hard to renovate the areas that have been destroyed by terrorists to restore normalcy.
The conditions are right now for the reception of asylum seekers back to the country after having to flee from terrorism and the harmful economic measures that targeted their daily lives and livelihoods.
The United Nations estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since the war began in 2011.
There is a need for humanitarian aid for the six million people still living in the country.
